You are implementing Task 2: Fix pipeline stuck run on DB error

## Task Description

In `src/factory/pipeline/mod.rs`, when the spawned pipeline task encounters a DB error checking cancellation status (around lines 820-838), it calls `return` which exits the spawned task WITHOUT updating the pipeline run status. This leaves the run permanently stuck in "Running" state.

**Current code (around lines 820-838):**
```rust
// Check if already cancelled (e.g., by cancel() call)
{
    let is_cancelled = match db
        .get_pipeline_run(run_id)
        .await
        .map(|r| r.is_some_and(|r| r.status == PipelineStatus::Cancelled))
    {
        Ok(cancelled) => cancelled,
        Err(e) => {
            eprintln!(
                "[pipeline] run_id={}: DB error checking cancellation: {:#}",
                run_id, e
            );
            return;  // <-- BUG: exits without updating status
        }
    };
    if is_cancelled {
        return;
    }
}
```

**Fix:** Before the `return`, attempt to mark the run as failed so it doesn't stay stuck. If that also fails, broadcast a WebSocket message so the UI gets notified:

```rust
Err(e) => {
    eprintln!(
        "[pipeline] run_id={}: DB error checking cancellation: {:#}",
        run_id, e
    );
    // Attempt to mark the run as failed so it doesn't stay stuck in "Running"
    let error_msg = format!("DB error during cancellation check: {e:#}");
    if let Err(e2) = db.update_pipeline_run(
        run_id,
        &PipelineStatus::Failed,
        None,
        Some(&error_msg),
    ).await {
        eprintln!(
            "[pipeline] run_id={}: CRITICAL: also failed to mark run as failed: {:#}",
            run_id, e2
        );
        // Last resort: broadcast so UI doesn't show "running" forever
        broadcast_message(&tx, &WsMessage::AgentSignal {
            run_id,
            task_id: 0,
            signal_type: SignalType::Blocker,
            content: format!("[pipeline] Run failed but could not persist status: {error_msg}"),
        });
    }
    return;
}
```

Note: The variables `db`, `run_id`, `tx`, `broadcast_message`, `WsMessage`, `PipelineStatus`, and `SignalType` are all already in scope at this location within the spawned task closure.

## Context

This is inside a `tokio::spawn` block in `PipelineRunner::run_pipeline()`. The `JoinHandle` is never awaited, so any early `return` exits the spawned task silently. The existing code already has a similar pattern at lines 892-904 where it handles DB errors on completion by broadcasting a WsMessage as a fallback.

